## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2020 Blackbaud data breach** — which I covered on Day 24 from the third-party risk perspective, but want to revisit specifically through the system boundary lens.

Blackbaud is a software provider used by hundreds of healthcare organizations for donor management and fundraising. When Blackbaud was breached, the data exposed belonged to the healthcare organizations that were Blackbaud's customers — not to Blackbaud itself. Those organizations had a system boundary that treated Blackbaud as an external vendor, outside the authorization boundary, governed by a Business Associate Agreement.

The breach exposed a critical gap in how boundary definitions and vendor assurance actually function in practice. The healthcare organizations had formal governance mechanisms in place — BAAs, vendor agreements — but those governance mechanisms did not provide visibility into Blackbaud's actual security posture. The BAA created legal accountability after the fact but did not prevent the breach or provide early warning.

The lesson for the system boundary work today is that governance mechanisms for external systems — BAAs, ISAs, vendor certifications — are necessary but not sufficient. The risk associated with external dependencies needs to be explicitly documented, actively monitored, and periodically reassessed. A BAA filed and forgotten is compliance theater. A BAA combined with annual vendor security review, contractual security requirements, and monitoring of vendor security advisories is meaningful third-party risk management.

For MyClinic's OpenMRS boundary, the external systems — the laboratory provider, the email service — need active governance, not just signed agreements.

